content.problemStatement:
In C++ programming, comparison operators allow us to compare values and check if they are equal or not.

- **Equality operator (==):** The equal to operator is used to check if two values are equal. It compares the left side value with the right side value and returns true if they are equal, otherwise false.

- **Not equal operator (!=):** The not equal to operator is used to check if two values are not equal. It compares the left side value with the right side value and returns true if they are not equal, otherwise false.

**Syntax**
```cpp
if (value1 == value2) {
    // Code to execute if value1 is equal to value2
}

if (value1 != value2) {
    // Code to execute if value1 is not equal to value2
}
```
---
**Example**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int a = 5;
    int b = 10;

    // Check if a is equal to b
    if (a == b) {
        cout << "a is equal to b" << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "a is not equal to b" << endl;  // This will execute as 5 != 10
    }

    // Check if a is not equal to b
    if (a != b) {
        cout << "a is not equal to b" << endl;  // This will execute as 5 != 10
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output**
```default
a is not equal to b
a is not equal to b
```

